{
  "id": "academorix://modules/region/data/country-defaults",
  "$version": 1,
  "title": "region — country defaults reference table",
  "description": "40+ countries mapped to their default { currency, currency_symbol, timezone, locale, rtl, weekend_days, tax_config, subdivision_note }. Loaded by RegionProvisioner when the caller supplies only country_code — every field the caller explicitly provides overrides its default. Reference material — read at boot + cached in-memory. Countries NOT in this table are refused by default when `region.validation.reject_unknown_country_code=true` (the default). Supranational zones (EU, GCC) require the config switch to be off + the caller supplies every field explicitly. This table is the source of truth for the ValidCountryCode rule in strict mode + the SDUI country picker.",
  "as_of": "2026-07-15",
  "notes": [
    "`weekend_days` values reflect the current legal/customary weekend for each country. Notable: UAE moved to [saturday,sunday] in Jan 2022; Saudi Arabia + Kuwait + Qatar + Oman + Bahrain + Jordan + Egypt still use [friday,saturday]; Iran uses [thursday,friday] (not shipped here).",
    "`tax_config.default_rate_percent` is the STANDARD/DEFAULT rate — reduced rates for children's programmes, food, etc. require the `region_custom_tax_rules` entitlement + the `rates[]` array.",
    "`tax_config.name` follows local convention: VAT (EU + AE + KSA + UK), GST (AU + NZ + CA + IN + SG), Sales Tax (US), TVA (FR — informal alias for VAT), IVA (ES + IT + MX + BR). US federal has no sales tax; state-level varies wildly — the shipped default is 0.000 with a note directing tenants to set the state's rate.",
    "`timezone_options` lists every legitimate IANA timezone for the country. `default_timezone` is the observer's pick when the caller omits timezone. Multi-tz countries (US, RU, AU, BR, CA, ID) list options top-to-bottom by 2026 population.",
    "`locale` uses BCP-47 with the country's largest first-language default. Bilingual/multilingual countries (CA, CH, BE) pick the dominant tag; the tenant may override.",
    "`rtl` derives from the locale — Arabic + Hebrew + Persian + Urdu locales carry `rtl: true`.",
    "Currency symbols use the localised glyph when it's a single character (`$`, `£`, `€`, `¥`, `₹`) and the 3-letter ISO code otherwise (`AED`, `SAR`, `NGN`) — the currency-formatting layer respects locale for placement + spacing."
  ],
